# 1. Obtain the Data: Get the Dogs vs Cats dataset (see class' notebook, only 5000, not 25,000, images are required, these image set is defined in the notebook)
import os, shutil, pathlib

#Original and new base path for the images downloaded
original_dir = pathlib.Path("/Users/dayapankajam/Desktop/archive/train/train")
new_base_dir = pathlib.Path("/Users/dayapankajam/Documents/AI")

def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ("cat", "dog"):
        #Creating the subdirectory
        subset_path = new_base_dir / subset_name / f"{category}s"
        os.makedirs(subset_path, exist_ok=True)
        #Iteration over the file names
        for i in range(start_index, end_index):
            fname = f"{category}.{i}.jpg"
            src = original_dir / fname
            dst = subset_path / fname
            if src.exists():
                shutil.copy2(src, dst)  # Use copy2 instead of copyfile
            else:
                print(f"File not Exists.")

#Creating subset for train, test and validations for reducing to 5000 dataset images.
make_subset("train", 0, 2000)        
make_subset("validation", 2000, 2250) 
make_subset("test", 2250, 2500)

def display_images(folder, title, n=5):
    pt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
    for i, img_path in enumerate(list(folder.glob('*.jpg'))[:n]):
        img = Image.open(img_path)
        pt.subplot(1, n, i + 1)
        pt.imshow(img)
        pt.axis('off')
        pt.title(f"{title} {i}")
    pt.show()

display_images(train_cats, "Cat")
display_images(train_dogs, "Dog")

#Extracting image sizes

for img_path in list(train_cats.glob('*.jpg'))[:100] + list(train_dogs.glob('*.jpg'))[:100]:
    try:
        with Image.open(img_path) as img:
            s.append(img.size)

        continue

# 3. Train two networks (use callbacks to save the best model version):
#    1. Define a Neural Network of your choice (3 points)

import tensorflow as tf
import pathlib
import numpy as np
import os
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models
from tensorflow.data import Dataset

#Setting the paths
train_dir = pathlib.Path("/Users/dayapankajam/Documents/AI/train/")
val_dir = pathlib.Path("/Users/dayapankajam/Documents/AI/validation/")

#Check if the directories exist and manually loading and preprocess the data
if not train_dir.exists() or not val_dir.exists():
    raise ValueError("Training or Validation directory not found.")

def load_images_from_directory(directory, image_size=(180, 180)):
    image_paths = list(directory.glob('*/*'))  # Get all images (subfolders for classes)
    image_paths = [str(path) for path in image_paths if path.is_file()]
    images = []
    labels = []
    class_names = sorted(os.listdir(directory))
    class_dict = {class_name: i for i, class_name in enumerate(class_names)}
    
    for img_path in image_paths:
        img = tf.io.read_file(img_path)
        img = tf.image.decode_jpeg(img, channels=3)
        img = tf.image.resize(img, image_size)
        img = tf.cast(img, tf.float32) / 255.0  # Rescale image
        label = class_dict[img_path.split('/')[-2]]  # Extract label based on folder name
        images.append(img)
        labels.append(label)
    images = np.array(images)
    labels = np.array(labels)
    return images, labels, class_names

#Loading the train and validation datasets
train_images, train_labels, train_class_names = load_images_from_directory(train_dir)
val_images, val_labels, val_class_names = load_images_from_directory(val_dir)

#Converting lists to TensorFlow Dataset, Shuffle and batch the datasets
train_set = Dataset.from_tensor_slices((train_images, train_labels))
val_set = Dataset.from_tensor_slices((val_images, val_labels))
train_set = train_set.shuffle(buffer_size=1000).batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.experimental.AUTOTUNE)
val_set = val_set.batch(32).prefetch(tf.data.experimental.AUTOTUNE)

#Building the neural network
model = models.Sequential([
    layers.Rescaling(1./255, input_shape=(180, 180, 3)),
    layers.Conv2D(32, 3, activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(),
    layers.Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(),
    layers.Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(),
    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

#Defining the callback for saving the best model manually
checkpoint_cb = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint("best_model.h5", save_best_only=True)

#Train and display the model
history = model.fit(train_set, validation_data=val_set, epochs=10, callbacks=[checkpoint_cb])
model.save('final_model.h5')
print("Best model saved as 'best_model.h5'.")

#2. Fine-Tune VGG16 (pre-trained on imagenet). Make sure to use validation to test for over-fitting. Plot the appropriate graph (3 points)

from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import GlobalAveragePooling2D, Dense

#Fine Tuning the VGG16 as a pre- trained on imagenet.
base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(180, 180, 3))
base_model.trainable = False

x = base_model.output
x = GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
result = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

vgg_model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=result)
vgg_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])

checkpoint_vgg = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint("best_vgg_model.h5", save_best_only=True)
history_vgg16 = vgg_model.fit(train_set, validation_data=val_set, epochs=10, callbacks=[checkpoint_vgg])

#Validating the overfitting plotting the accuracy and loss
#Plotting training & validation accuracy/loss

import matplotlib.pyplot as pt
def plot_training(history, title='Model'):
    accuracy = history.history['accuracy']
    val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    epochs = range(1, len(accuracy) + 1)

    pt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
    pt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    pt.plot(epochs, accuracy, 'bo', label='Training acc')
    pt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation acc')
    pt.title(f'{title} - Training and Validation Accuracy')
    pt.legend()

    pt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    pt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
    pt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss')
    pt.title(f'{title} - Training and Validation Loss')
    pt.legend()
    pt.show()

plot_training(history_vgg16, title='VGG16 Fine-Tuned Model')

def get_metrics(model, test_ds):
    y_true = np.concatenate([y.numpy() for x, y in test_ds])
    y_pred = model.predict(test_ds).ravel()
    y_pred_label = (y_pred > 0.5).astype(int)

    print(f"VGG16 Fine-tuned Accuracy: ", vgg_acc)

    pt.title("Precision-Recall Curve")

    pt.ylabel("Precision")

from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_precision_recall(model, test_ds, model_name="Model"):
    y_true = np.concatenate([y.numpy() for _, y in test_ds])
    y_pred_probs = model.predict(test_ds).ravel()
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_pred_probs)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=model_name)
    plt.xlabel("Recall")
    plt.ylabel("Precision")
    plt.title(f"Precision-Recall Curve: {model_name}")
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

#Plotting the precision recall
plot_precision_recall(best_cnn_model, test_set, model_name="CNN")
plot_precision_recall(best_vgg_model, test_set, model_name="Fine-tuned VGG16")

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

def print_classification_report(model, test_ds):
    y_true = np.concatenate([y.numpy() for _, y in test_ds])
    y_pred_probs = model.predict(test_ds).ravel()
    y_pred = (y_pred_probs > 0.5).astype(int)

    print("Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=["Cat", "Dog"]))
print("CNN Classification Report:")

#4.precision-recall curve.
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_precision_recall(model, test_set, model_name="Model"):
    y_true = np.concatenate([y.numpy() for _, y in test_set])
    y_pred_probs = model.predict(test_set).ravel()
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_pred_probs)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=model_name)
    plt.xlabel("Recall")
    plt.ylabel("Precision")
    plt.title(f"Precision-Recall Curve: {model_name}")
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

#Plot the recision- recall curve
plot_precision_recall(best_cnn_model, test_set, model_name="CNN")
plot_precision_recall(best_vgg_model, test_set, model_name="Fine-tuned VGG16")

#5.Explore specific examples in which the model failed to predict correctly.

#Displaying the misclassified images from VGG16
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def show_misclassified(model, test_ds):
    class_names = test_ds.class_names
    y_true = np.concatenate([y.numpy() for x, y in test_ds])
    y_pred = model.predict(test_ds).ravel()
    y_pred_label = (y_pred > 0.5).astype(int)

    misclassified = np.where(y_true != y_pred_label)[0]

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    for i, (x, _) in enumerate(test_ds.unbatch().take(len(misclassified))):
        if i in misclassified[:9]:
            ax = plt.subplot(3, 3, i+1)
            plt.imshow(x.numpy().astype("uint8"))
            plt.title(f"Predicted: {class_names[y_pred_label[i]]}, True: {class_names[int(y_true[i])]}")
            plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

show_misclassified(vgg_model, test_set)

5. Add your conclusions. (3 point)

Model Evaluation Summary:

  • The CNN performed well but it overfitting in the end of epochs and the VGG16 Outperformed the custom model with the higher validation and test accuracy.
  • The Confusion Matrix & Classification Report with percision, F1 score for VGG16 showed higher precision and recall for both classes. It will be the Fewer misclassifications.
  • The precision recall Curve for VGG16 maintained a better balance between precision and recall, especially at higher recall levels.

Failure Analysis: The Misclassifications occurred when images were not clear. This can be improved using data augmentation or more training data.

Conclusion: Fine-tuning a pretrained model like VGG16 gives a significant performance boost over training a CNN from the starting, especially when the dataset is limited to only 5000 images. The pre-trained model benefits from features learned on larger datasets and generalizes better to the new data.
